title: $:/plugins/rimir/msg-import/readme
type: text/vnd.tiddlywiki

! MSG Import

Drop Outlook `.msg` ''or'' RFC 5322 `.eml` files into a `<$file-dropzone>` and get a clean markdown tiddler with YAML frontmatter, plus the attachments as artifact child tiddlers.

The original blob is preserved as the canonical asset under `files/email/`, so the email is still re-downloadable.

Format dispatch is by filename extension: `.msg` is parsed via the `extract-msg` Python library (Outlook binary format), `.eml` via Python's stdlib `email` module (RFC 5322 plain text). Both paths produce the same output tiddler shape and downstream rendering — same `.email` artifact, same attachment row, same cascade behaviour.

!! Key Features

* ''Drag-and-drop import'' — works in any `<$file-dropzone>` for both `application/vnd.ms-outlook` (`.msg`) and `message/rfc822` (`.eml`); both MIME types are allow-listed by file-upload ≥ 0.1.24
* ''Frontmatter metadata'' — subject, from, to, cc, bcc, date, message-id, in-reply-to extracted into YAML fields (handled by `rimir/frontmatter` for round-trip)
* ''HTML → markdown'' — email body converted via pandoc (no shell, no filename arg → no injection)
* ''Attachments are first-class'' — each non-inline attachment becomes a child tiddler with `_artifact_source` linking back to the parent .msg, typed by its filename extension (PDF, DOCX, .msg, …) and AUTOMATICALLY routed through its own MIME-matched pipeline. A PDF attachment gets the PDF pipeline (thumbnail + text extraction); an attached `.msg` recursively produces its own `.email` and processes its own attachments. Cycle protection via per-recursion `seen` map of URIs
* ''Confirmed deletion'' — deleting any uploaded media (incl. the parent `.msg`) opens a modal listing the full transitive cascade and every backlinking tiddler before nuking. Toggle via `$:/config/rimir/file-upload/confirm-deletes`
* ''Inline images preserved'' — `cid:` references in the body are rewritten to wiki-relative URLs pointing at the saved inline-image files
* ''Optional LLM summary'' — gated by `$:/config/rimir/msg-import/llm-summary`; mirrors the `docx-llm` pipeline
* ''Executable quarantine'' — `.exe`, `.bat`, `.ps1`, `.vbs`, `.jar` etc. are listed in the frontmatter as `msg-quarantined-attachments` and not written to disk (configurable)

!! Prerequisites

* ''rimir/file-upload'' — drop handling, the `application/vnd.ms-outlook` MIME entry (≥ 0.1.20) and the `message/rfc822` MIME entry (≥ 0.1.24)
* ''rimir/file-pipeline'' — pipeline executor; this plugin contributes one pipeline tiddler matching both MIME types
* ''rimir/runner'' — the runner actions live in `dev-wiki/runner-actions.json`
* ''rimir/frontmatter'' — `text/x-frontmattered-markdown` deserializer and save-patch
* ''Python 3'' — stdlib only for `.eml` parsing; `pip install extract-msg` is needed only if you intend to drop `.msg` files
* ''pandoc'' on `PATH` — used by both formats to convert the HTML body to markdown

!! Install

# Install the plugin (drop the plugin folder under `dev-wiki/plugins/rimir/msg-import/`).
# Add `"rimir/msg-import"` to your wiki's `tiddlywiki.info` plugin list.
# Merge the two entries from `runner-actions/msg.json` into `dev-wiki/runner-actions.json` (restart the server after — runner-actions are read at boot).
# `pip install -r dev-wiki/plugins/rimir/msg-import/scripts/requirements.txt` in the Python environment your runner shells out to.
# Confirm `pandoc --version` works on the server's `PATH`.

!! Output Shape

For an imported `meeting.msg` (or `meeting.eml`), three tiddler groups are created:

* `meeting.msg` — the original binary, `type: application/vnd.ms-outlook` (or `message/rfc822` for `.eml`), with `_canonical_uri = /files/email/meeting.msg`
* `meeting.msg.email` — the markdown body, `type: text/x-frontmattered-markdown`; frontmatter carries the metadata
* `meeting.msg.attachments/<filename>` — one tiddler per attachment, each with `_artifact_source = meeting.msg` and `_artifact_type = attachment`

Renaming the parent cascades through all three groups via the file-upload artifact cascade. Same for delete.
